text: we can journal about our hopes and dreams all we want.  but, if we don’t work for it, it won’t happen.  the best way to make our dreams a reality and become successful is to plan.  spend some time today planning for this week and the new year - what are your goals, what steps do you need to take to complete your goals, and how will you do so?  yes, you can do this - but you need to plan 💜

text:
kadinlarin yili!
2018 kadınların sesinin yükseldiği, kadın devriminin dünyanın dört bir yanında hissedildiği bir yıl olarak tarihe geçiyor. 2018 kadınların yılıydı!
2018 hareketimiz için oldukça önemli bir yıldı çünkü kuruluşumuzun 10. yılını kutladık. i̇lk 10 yılımızı erkek egemenliğine karşı sesimizi yükselterek ve dünyanın dört köşesinde kızkardeşlik bağımızı güçlendirerek tamamladık ve geleceğe dair umutlarımızı ve hayallerimizi taşımaya devam ediyoruz. ukrayna’dan fransa’ya ve tüm dünyaya yayıldık. kievli öğrencilerden fransa, almanya, i̇spanya, i̇sveç, hollanda, belçika, meksika, brezilya, türkiye, abd, venezuela ve çek cumhuriyeti’ndeki farklı yaş ve kimliklerdeki kadınlara... femen’in bugüne kadarki yolculuğu bu şekildeydi ve bundan sonrası için daha da büyümeye hazırız.
2018’de femen tc cumhurbaşkanı recep tayyip erdoğan ve abd başkanı donald trump gibi iktidardaki güçlü erkeklere meydan okumaya devam etti. trump’ın şanzelize’den geçmekte olan konvoyu femen aktivistleri tarafından iki kez durduruldu.
2018’de tüm dünyada yankı bulan #metoo akımında femen de yer aldı. ünlü erkeklere kadın bedeninin her zaman onların emrindeki cinsel objeler olmadığını hatırlattık. kadın bedenini öfkeli ve yüksek çıkan seslere dönüştürdük. woody allen ve roman polanski’den sonra 2018’de de silvio berlusconi ve bill cosby ile yüz yüze gelmeyi başardık.
2018’de her zaman savunduğumuz lgbti̇+ haklarını savunmaya devam ettik ve fransa’daki eşcinselleri kapsamayan sağlık hizmetinden rusya, tunus ve mısır’daki nefret suçlarına kadar birçok konuda sesimizi yükselttik. almanya ve i̇spanya’da kürtaj hakkımız için mücadele ettik. aynı zamanda avrupa genelinde sağcı grupların yabancı düşmanlığına ve ırkçılığına karşı da femen olarak savaşmaya devam ettik.
i̇fade özgürlüğünü kullandıkları için çeşitli yaptırımlara maruz bırakılan kahramanlar olarak gördüğümüz pakistan’dan asia bibi, rusya’dan oleg sentsov, fransa’dan petr pavlensky’yi savunduk.
dünya 2018’de kadın eylemleriyle sarsıldı ve femen bunun bir parçası olmaktan gurur duyuyor. kadınların abd, brezilya ve şili’de femen taktiğini kullanarak bedenlerini politik eylem aracına dönüştürdüklerini gördük. ⬇️
name: FEMEN Turkey

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text: i am best at expressing my emotions in what i am saying when i am singing. the lyrics to this song represent someone who has been in a toxic relationship, and in this case, that someone is me. if you listen to this song carefully, it all represents what one goes through after they get out of a bad relationship: this is what i went through, and it was terrible: the shame, the guilt, the self-loathing, but none of it was my fault. it is never your fault when someone abuses you. when it’s not just #metoo or #timesup, and it’s more like #enddomesticviolence, and #enddomesticabuse. i am a #domesticabusesurvivor. #survivorspeaks

text:
while the last few years have been challenging, i am grateful to the part of me years ago which decided that the suffering i endured had reached my ‘enough’ line. ••
•• 🐞i wish i had not being so patient, but the suffering made it so clear to not let anyone limit or control my joy, feelings, choices & life. i have again through different circumstances being reminded that when life throws you life events out of your control to get activated & refuse to let others or the past define your future & what is possible now. ••
•• 🦋tell yourself, i have got through everything so far. the universe has my back. i’ve got this. surround yourself with an inner cheersquad team of people who want the best for you! feel it, dream it. be grateful for everything that is. •• •• 🐞when i escaped & i felt that joy bubbling through me & the relief that i could feel joy no matter how he was trying to control & punish me i focussed on the numerous good things in my life. i didn’t focus on the constant court appearances, single parenting challenges or financial struggles, i focused on my girls, my new home, the meal i was preparing & the daily peace. what are you grateful for?

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
no somos lo que ven de nosotros. 
no somos lo que transmitimos. ya no.

sé que parece complicado pero hemos llegado a un punto en la sociedad que está mal visto expresar las emociones. tenemos que guardarlas para nosotros mismos. y obvio si eres mujer mucho peor: no debes hablar de sexo, mostrarte segura de ti misma o emborracharte porque te apetezca (entre otras muchas cosas). muchas veces acusan a las mujeres de que “no se explican” o “no se las entiende”. quizá el problema es que cada vez vamos encerrándonos más en nosotras mismas, ocultando nuestras emociones y sentimientos, haciendo caso omiso a los problemas que realmente los afectan... todo por no ser juzgadas. y no solo eso, ser juzgadas puede traer consecuencias personales, laborales y sociales. 
conozco a muchas mujeres (y me incluyo) que hemos sufrido por lo que han dicho los demás, porque se han creado mentiras en torno a nosotras que los demás han creído. ¿por qué no dedicamos un segundo a preguntar al afectado? ¿por qué no intentamos empatizar? ¿por qué no nos hacemos estas preguntas?

vamos hacia un mundo mucho más insensible, lleno de corazones recubiertos de armaduras para no sufrir. y yo, admito que me da muchísima pena, porque no hay nada más bonito que ver incluso a desconocimos expresar sus emociones como si fueran niños de nuevo, sin importar lo que digan los demás. ojalá, todos volviéramos a sentir como niños de este 2019.

se lo pediré a los reyes magos desde lo más profundo de mi corazón.

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied. 
in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied. 
in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
a few months later, in autumn 2013, wylie met steve bannon. at the time, he was editor-in-chief of breitbart, which he had brought to britain to support his friend nigel farage in his mission to take britain out of the european union.

what was he like? - smart, says wylie. - interesting. really interested in ideas. he’s the only straight man i’ve ever talked to about intersectional feminist theory. he saw its relevance straightaway to the oppressions that conservative, young white men feel.

wylie meeting bannon was the moment petrol was poured on a flickering flame. wylie lives for ideas. he speaks 19 to the dozen for hours at a time. he had a theory to prove. and at the time, this was a purely intellectual problem. politics was like fashion, he told bannon.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied. 
in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied. 
in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied. 
in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

vilket år ändå♥️. min andra bok #värstabästanätet landade i handeln den 14 aug och har idag sålt drygt 8000 ex. 
jag vill fira våra nya superviktiga lagrum (googla för mer info) som kommit oss till gagn under året: olaga integritetsintrång och den nya sexualbrottslagstiftningen som kräver samtycke vid sex (aka samtyckeslagstiftningen). #metoo är inget annat än att vara tacksam för; sååå många berättelser som kullkastat inte bara #svenskaakademien utan även andra vidriga och farliga strukturer.

2018 innebar massor fantastiska resor i hela sverige, ännu fler unika och magiska möten med såå många fina och kämpande människor: elever, kuratorer, lärare, olika positioner på olika kommuner som kämpar för att driva kunskapen på orten, föräldrar, mor- och farföräldrar, fritidspersonal, grannar och syskon♥️. tack för alla förtroenden jag fått, alla dm, mail och telefonsamtal: era berättelser utvecklar mitt arbete och gör världen mer medveten för att dem som får lära av er🙏🏼 nu har vi bara några timmar kvar av 2018 och jag känner enorm tacksamhet, styrka, driv och längtan efter mer: 2019 ser m y c k e t lovande ut. låt oss kämpa vidare nästa år för helt ärligt: kämpandet får effekt♥️

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied. 
in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
penúltimo día del año. un año con luces y sombras. 2018 no ha sido fácil aunque gracias a los míos todo se lleva mejor

en este año del #metoo he conocido mujeres increíbles, luchadoras y currantas como @miss_herisson @yarapuebla @2_be__fit @myriam_viudes @kekamartineztv @barbaracrespo . a otras les he tenido que echar de menos a la fuerza. una fuerza que a veces me ha desgastado el corazón y las lágrimas @susanapereztv @rociosantosoficial  @lorraine_mansi y la mujer de mi vida... la radio

en julio nos dijimos adiós y me juro no volver a verte... pero la calidad de personas que la hacen, mi profesión y el amor por las ondas no me permiten no echarte de menos... ni a ti @europafm, ni a ti mi diamante en bruto @pabloguerola 
ni a vosotros compañeros de onda cero @raulgranado10 @albertopereiro @hfernandez @david.alonsooc etc

mis sombras se tornan en luz cuando siento tus patadas. en mayo supimos que vendrías al mundo... tu hermano #da rápidamente te buscó nombre : #marcos. ahora que me quedan días para mirarnos a los ojos sólo puedo pensar en tanto bien como ya me has dado... a mí y a toda tu familia que ya te quiere sin conocerte

y como no... a ellos que conducen mi bipolaridad, mis cambios de humor, mis mañanas sin hablar, mis hormonas alteradas. qué en julio ante un fin de semana de malas noticias me arroparon como hermanos mayores @carmencitaindia @javiergil73 #bbto...y a mis padres... con los que el término justicia y amor a veces se me va de las manos

y como no... a ti mi amor @doncarballo por esa rosa blanca de julio, por tu silencio cuando merezco un grito, por nuestra casita de madera en asturias, por ser el mejor padre del mundo y quererme sin condiciones... y por supuesto por ese anillo de san sebastián 14 años después de conocernos. en el mismo lugar un sí quiero ❤️ sólo rezo y pido a dios que este 2019 no me separe de nosotros, sí de nosotros... ya que el vosotros ya me queda lejos. me de un trabajo honrado y todo el amor del mundo. lo mismo les deseo yo a ellos. gente buena y trabajadora de la que aprendo y con la que me divierto. mi mayor riqueza.

#mybest2018 #best2018 #happynewyear #girlonfire #journalist #mumtobe #2018bestnine #2018

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied. 
in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
christopher wylie, who worked with a cambridge university academic to obtain the data, told the observer: “we exploited facebook to harvest millions of people’s profiles. and built models to exploit what we knew about them and target their inner demons. that was the basis the entire company was built on.” documents seen by the observer, and confirmed by a facebook statement, show that by late 2015 the company had found out that information had been harvested on an unprecedented scale. however, at the time it failed to alert users and took only limited steps to recover and secure the private information of more than 50 million individuals.

the data was collected through an app called thisisyourdigitallife, built by academic aleksandr kogan, separately from his work at cambridge university. through his company global science research (gsr), in collaboration with cambridge analytica, hundreds of thousands of users were paid to take a personality test and agreed to have their data collected for academic use.

however, the app also collected the information of the test-takers’ facebook friends, leading to the accumulation of a data pool tens of millions-strong. facebook’s “platform policy” allowed only collection of friends’ data to improve user experience in the app and barred it being sold on or used for advertising. the discovery of the unprecedented data harvesting, and the use to which it was put, raises urgent new questions about facebook’s role in targeting voters in the us presidential election. it comes only weeks after indictments of 13 russians by the special counsel robert mueller which stated they had used the platform to perpetrate “information warfare” against the us.

carole cadwalladr & emma graham-harrison
the guardian

christopher wylie, who worked with a cambridge university academic to obtain the data, told the observer: “we exploited facebook to harvest millions of people’s profiles. and built models to exploit what we knew about them and target their inner demons. that was the basis the entire company was built on.” documents seen by the observer, and confirmed by a facebook statement, show that by late 2015 the company had found out that information had been harvested on an unprecedented scale. however, at the time it failed to ale users and took only limited steps to recover and secure the private information of more than 50 million individuals.

the data was collected through an app called thisisyourdigitallife, built by academic aleksandr kogan, separately from his work at cambridge university. through his company global science research (gsr), in collaboration with cambridge analytica, hundreds of thousands of users were paid to take a personality test and agreed to have their data collected for academic use.

however, the app also collected the information of the test-takers’ facebook friends, leading to the accumulation of a data pool tens of millions-strong. facebook’s “platform policy” allowed only collection of friends’ data to improve user experience in the app and barred it being sold on or used for adveising. the discovery of the unprecedented data harvesting, and the use to which it was put, raises urgent new questions about facebook’s role in targeting voters in the us presidential election. it comes only weeks after indictments of 13 russians by the special counsel robe mueller which stated they had used the platform to perpetrate “information warfare” against the us.

text:
i'm not making any resolutions for next year. i made a lot of changes this year, few of which were easy, all of which have made me feel like i'm living with more integrity. more integrity (and better skin). more integrity (and better hair). 1. fat is good for you. this is the year i gave up skimmed everything and went all-out full-fat. i rediscovered cheese. i put butter in everything. i ate more salt than i had done my entire life previously. i iearned, in short, to taste food again.

2.  go for the chop. "are you sure?" asked my hairdresser. "i've had a bad two years. this hair has seen some shit. take it all off please"

if you're in doubt, a haircut reminds you that you are never bound to being who you were, or thinking what you thought, or feeling what you felt.

3. fighting the patriarchy is easier in a team. full disclosure, it took me months to get on board with #metoo. i'm not proud. but this year i realised it was because of the rock solid guilt i'd been living with at having put up with (and, by association, sanctioning) next level amounts of minor harassment and talking about women as though they're there for the taking.

so, this year, i changed my behaviour and my attitude to casual misogyny. and this year i stopped tolerating that behaviour in others. it's lost me some people. it's gained me integrity.

4. douse your face in acid (the good kind). i've tried all sorts of new skincare this year. it turns out my skin likes being gobbled up from the outside in the form of fruit acids. aesthetics aside, there's something incredibly soothing about taking the time out twice a day to look at yourself close up in the mirror and layer witchcraft products on your skin that accomplish no more than serve you to look your best. you are worth the effort and the time.

5. i got a promotion. i left the place i'd worked for over a decade and i started somewhere where i knew nobody, or anything about the subject area. it was bloody terrifying and bloody exhilarating to have to rely on my wits. it aged me ten years (good thing i'd discovered hyaluronic acid, eh) but oh did it make me  realise i can push myself off a cliff and land on my feet.

text:
the year of #women

2018 marked another historic uprising of female voices, another high-point of the women's revolution that is taking place across the world. #2018 was the year of women. 
2018 was remarkable year for our movement as we celebrated the 10th anniversary of #femen. the first decade of our history ends with pride for numerous fights against male domination, with sisterhood among the activists in 4 corners of the planet and with dreams and aspirations for the future. from ukraine to france and to the rest of the world. from kiev students, to women of different age and backgrounds in france, germany, spain, sweden, netherlands, belgium, mexico, brazil, turkey, the usa, venezuela and czech republic. that's the journey femen made so far and we are now ready to expand further. 
in 2018, femen continued to give a sextremist lesson to the patriarchs in power like turkish president recep erdogan and the us president donald trump. driving across the champs-elysees in paris, trump's motorcade was stoped twice by our angry political bodies. that's our female revenge. that's how we grab back patriarchy by the balls! 
in 2018 femen also contributed to the worldwide female uprising #metoo. our activists chased the celebrity perpetrators and made sure they learn that female bodies aren't always sexual objects at their disposal. we made them hear angry loud female voices. following our actions against woody allen and roman polanski, in 2018 we've faced again silvio berlusconi and finally caught bill cosby as he was about to be sentenced for numerous crimes. 
2018 was the year of women with numerous victories for women in different countries. yet, the fight isn't over. it is only the beginning of the next step in our revolution. femen prepares itself for the next year of female fight and femen is ready for the second decade of our topless revolt. with new branches in venezuela and czech republic, with new ideas and strategies, with the same anger and courage, our female soldiers are ready to continue the peaceful fight for equality and dignity of everyone. 
let 2019 be the year of equality, justice and peace. let's make 2019 the year of women again! #feminism
name: Inna Shevchenko FEMEN

2018 was remarkable year for our movement as we celebrated the 10th anniversary of #femen. the first decade of our history ends with pride for numerous fights against male domination, with sisterhood among the activists in 4 corners of the planet and with dreams and aspirations for the future. from ukraine to france and to the rest of the world. from kiev students, to women of different age and backgrounds in france, germany, spain, sweden, netherlands, belgium, mexico, brazil, turkey, the usa, venezuela and czech republic. that's the journey femen made so far and we are now ready to expand further. 
in 2018, femen continued to give a sextremist lesson to the patriarchs in power like turkish president recep erdogan and the us president donald trump. driving across the champs-elysees in paris, trump's motorcade was stoped twice by our angry political bodies. that's our female revenge. that's how we grab back patriarchy by the balls! 
in 2018 femen also contributed to the worldwide female uprising #metoo. our activists chased the celebrity perpetrators and made sure they learn that female bodies are not always sexual objects at their disposal. we made them hear angry loud female voices. following our actions against woody allen and roman polanski, in 2018 we've faced again silvio berlusconi and finally caught bill cosby as he was about to be sentenced for numerous crimes. 
2018 was the year of women with numerous victories for women in different countries. yet, the fight is not over. it is only the beginning of the next step in our revolution. femen prepares itself for the next year of female fight and femen is ready for the second decade of our topless revolt. with new branches in venezuela and czech republic, with new ideas and strategies, with the same anger and courage, our female soldiers are ready to continue the peaceful fight for equality and dignity of everyone. 
let 2019 be the year of equality, justice and peace. let's make 2019 the year of women again! #feminism

text:
luin viikon sisään kaksi erinomaista kirjaa, everyday sexism ja #metoo-vallankumous - miten hiljaisuus rikottiin. kumpikin käsittelee seksismiä, bates laajemmin ja lindén sitten liittyen tähän elokuva- ja teatterialan vallankumoukseen.
.
bates kokoaa kirjaan ison liudan kokemuksia, jotka saavat suoraan sanottuna aika hirveän olon aikaan. silti kirjan lukeminen oli voimaannuttavaa ja rohkaisi todella paljon. onhan se aika hirveää huomata, että on joskus ollut työyhteisössä, jossa ei ole vuoroakaan saanut tehdä ilman seksismiä. harmi vain, ettei sitä ymmärtänyt niin nuorena.
.
lindénin kirjassa käydään läpi, miten metoo-kampanja löi suomessa läpi, miten naisten äänet saatiin lopulta kuuluviin ja mitä kaikkea kulissien takana on tapahtunut. kirjan lopussa oli sivukaupalla kokemuksia elokuvamaailman häirintätapauksista. luin sitä aivan järkyttyneenä, vaikka olinkin tietoinen kyseisistä tapauksista.
.
nämä kirjat saivat aikaan ihan suunnatonta raivoa ja turhautumista. toisaalta taas tunnen olevani naiseuteni kanssa enemmän sinut kuin koskaan, tunnen olevani voimakas ja että en enää koskaan ole hiljaa. mä olen aivan äärettömän ylpeä tästä suomen elokuva-alan vallankumouksesta ja sen käynnistäneistä ihmisistä. 💪
.
seuraava lukemista odottava feministinen kirja on tuo jessica bennettin feminist fight club.
.
"emme enää katso sivusta. emme enää suvaitse. emme enää vaikene koskaan. vallankumous on tapahtunut."
.

text:
sentenced four years in jail for molesting minor.

salim chhelawala, 44 year old, had molested the 8 year old girl whilehe was driving her towards her school in karelibauh on september 17, 2016.

he later touched the girl inappropriately and molested her. the girl was
shocked and chhelawala even threatened to beat her if she told her parents about the incident.

however, the girl informed her parents and chhelawala was booked for molestation,
criminal intimidation and violation of protection of children from sexual offences (pocso) act at city police station.

following an fir, the court upheld arguments of additional public prosecutor n u
makwana and convicted chhelawala. “the girl’s statement was registered before amagistrate under section 164 of criminal procedure code which made it importantevidence. during the hearing of the case too, her testimony and her father’s
testimony were also important,” said makwana.

besides sentencing him to jail, the court of additional sessions judge a a nanavatialso fined chhelawala of rs 10,000. toi©

#repost @femen_official (@get_repost)
・・・
the year of women

2018 marked another historic uprising of female voices, another high-point of the women's revolution that is taking place across the world. #2018 was the year of #women. 
2018 was remarkable year for our movement as we celebrated the 10th anniversary of #femen. the first decade of our history ends with pride for numerous fights against male domination, with sisterhood among the activists in 4 corners of the planet and with dreams and aspirations for the future. from #ukraine to #france and to the rest of the world. from kiev students, to women of different age and backgrounds in france, germany, spain, sweden, netherlands, belgium, mexico, brazil, turkey, the usa, venezuela and czech republic. that's the journey femen made so far and we are now ready to expand further. 
in 2018, femen continued to give a sextremist lesson to the patriarchs in power like turkish president recep #erdogan and the us president donald #trump. driving across the champs-elysees in paris, trump's motorcade was stoped twice by our angry political bodies. that's our female revenge. that's how we grab back #patriarchy by the balls! 
in 2018 femen also contributed to the worldwide female uprising #metoo. our activists chased the celebrity perpetrators and made sure they learn that female bodies aren't always sexual objects at their disposal. we made them hear angry loud female voices. following our actions against woody allen and roman polanski, in 2018 we've faced again silvio berlusconi and finally caught bill cosby as he was about to be sentenced for numerous crimes. 
in 2018 we've denounced #homophobia of conservative groups who deny the rights of gay couples for medically assisted procreation in france as well as the hate crimes against #lgbt+ community in putin's russia, in tunisia and egypt. we've defended our abortion rights with protests in germany and spain and raised up against xenophobia and sexism of the far right groups across europe. 
in 2018 we stood with heroes of freedom of speech and consciences like asia bibi in pakistan and oleg sentsov in russia. femen also supported the imprisoned in france artist pyotr pavl

text:
this year has been a year of major growth for myself and for women all over the world. 
that being said, i feel like after 11 years of not sharing my story, now is the time. ❗ages 12-34 are the highest risk years for rape and sexual assault
❗ 1 out of every 6 women has been a victim of an attempted or completed rape in her lifetime.
❗ females ages 16-19 are 4 times more likely than the general population to be victims of rape, attempted rape, or sexual assault
❗ 1 out of every 10 rape victims are male
❗ 21% of tgqn (transgender, genderqueer, nonconforming) college students have been sexually assaulted, compared to 18% of non-tgqn females, and 4% of non-tgqn males.
❗ 33% of women who are raped contemplate suicide.
❗ 13% of women who are raped attempt suicide. 
https://www.rainn.org/statistics/victims-sexual-violence

i was one of those girls at just 15 years old and with a very trusted friend when i had a little too much to drink at a party. fast forward a few hours and my innocence was taken from me by a man close to 10 years my senior. it happens that quick. in the blink of an eye, your life will change. in the blink of an eye, your girlhood vanishes. 
losing your innocence is your choice, not someone else's. regardless of alcohol, substance, or anything else involved, no excuse in the world exists. 
here is to 2019. may it be another year of growth, education, enlightenment, and togetherness for women like the universe has never seen before. 📞 +18006564673 for help

text:
the students of howard university film and television program call for the establishment of a department of cinematic arts and television, effective fall 2019. howard has the most comprehensive film program, and offers the only mfa in film, of any hbcu in the united states. howard university has the only minority owned pbs affiliate in the nation. for decades since the founding of the film program in 1971, we have been fulfilling a national and global need for women storytellers and storytellers of color. still, there is no hbcu in the united states with a department dedicated to the study of cinematic arts and television - we can change this.

we are calling for the first department of cinematic arts and television, at any hbcu in the nation, to include the following components:

a) independently administered budget. 
b) independently managed equipment center and facilities. 
c) shared governance by the students and faculty over said budget, equipment center, curriculum development and implementation of the undergraduate and graduate bfa and mfa programs, as well as program and instructor evaluation. 
d) and a commitment to attract more of the most qualified professors in the industry, and to continue to produce graduates of the finest caliber.

support us by signing the petition, share the campaign with everyone you know, and let howard university president wayne a. i. frederick know that the time is now for a howard university department of cinematic arts and television.

since 1971, the howard university film program has produced and/or supported the most highly trained and widely acclaimed storytellers, including: bradford young, hans charles, ernest dickerson, arthur jafa, jenn nkiru, malik sayeed, alan ferguson, sehkar kammula, faraday okoro, lodi matsetela, lekgetho makola, nijla mumin, maori karmael holmes, floyd rance, yao ramesar, and shirikiana aina.

with the likes of stanley nelson, michelle parkerson, julie dash, and haile gerima having served as faculty in the program.

in the new era of #oscarssowhite, #timesup, and #metoo the film and television industry is clearing space to #tellblackstories.

text:
#interraciallovestory  #loveislovestory™🏳️‍🌈 + #climateaction gender debate "eve n'god this female is not yet rated ™" opens  feb 1, 2019 for a one week run through feb 7, 2019.  the " #freshoffthegrid™ #handmade " new indie run, follows immediately after #thefavourite runs.
eve n'god this female is not yet rated ™  plays 3 shows a day, #dtla  @downtownindependent cinema :  251 s. main street, la  90012  ph. (213) 617- 1033 
the allegorical #avantgarde fairytale is described as “1 day in the epiphany of a 21st century girl, who kissed a girl ™ a lost+found virginity #fantasy bordering on polyamory ; a bittersweet romance in the key of rock n’ #soul ; an immersive  floating #scifi dream as global girl awakens to the legacy of herself.” the all-female crew production from actressauteur™  cali lili + her #sustainable #upcycled movie + music studio in #gentrification -torn venice beach canals with #oceanconservancy footage including a local octopus named "octavia" + other #sealife appearing unprompted 4 the lens during principal photography was made w 90% upcycled original costumes + sets farmersmarket items for "garden of eve" set.
co-stars legendary indie spirits award nominee, iconic actor/musician #wingshauser as lead male role, doctor godard / aka "god" with cali lili as "eve," and candace burney as “lila." certified on imdb as “ #triplefrated ” meaning it was written, directed and produced by a woman, making it one of the first (maybe the first) narrative motion pictures made primarily by women . the project originated, in part, as a response to cali lili's own " #metoo " experiences promotion of “all female on-the-set crew” began pre-production as far back as 2011 likely setting the current trend - against all odds, weathering early discriminatory push-backs from various directions. #lesbiancinema #lgbtqmovie #lgbtstem
dedicated 2 victims of violence against lgbtqcommunities women #indigenouscommunities wildlife + #environment - the #feministmovie is described as "breaking the sound barrier" referencing the lead female who "speaks over 51% of the film," "shattering narrative structures +  glassceilings "ctd. soundtrack #soul #rock #rap
#firsttimedirector

text:
for all those who are suffering with this pain in silence. i hear you. #metoo
| the issue: having to consent to sex in marriage (or in a committed relationship), not being able to say no without being blamed, bullied, forced, pursued, abused, nagged, persisted, coerced, threatened, demanded, demeaned, etc; and/or the no is not respected; and worse so, being forced upon and it is not: punished, held accountable, or it is simply dismissed; or even worse so, the victim can not even bring it up as an issues, as it is so deeply seeped into custom and society as a non-issue. where a woman is expected to cater to the man, with sex— as he pleases, when he wishes it, even while he is being an abusive partner with this and/or other things. marriage does not mean obligated access and duty of sex. consent— unwilling, forced, coerced is all non consent. @ninnukoripoetry

text:
я хочу , чтобы ты верил в себя
🎄  на свете нет такого же человека, как ты. ты можешь играть особую роль в этом мире и в чьей-то жизни. мир обеднеет без твоего особенного вклада в него. он нуждается в тебе.
⠀
🎄  твоя жизнь – это дар. ты прекрасный человек. будь самой лучшей версией себя. ведь это по-настоящему здорово жить и осознавать тот факт, что ты не просто мяско с эмоциями, а человек, который заботиться о себе и привносит в этот мир чуточку больше духовной красоты и эстетики.
⠀
🎄  ты был создан, чтобы тебя любили, желали и ценили. дело не в том, чтобы принять или смириться с тем, кто ты есть. ты был создан, чтобы тебя ценили и уважали другие люди. и, конечно же, ты сам.
⠀
🎄  ты был создан, чтобы у тебя была цель и ты шёл к своим мечтам – чтобы в конце осознать, что ты смог этого достичь и что твоя жизнь имеет смысл. с каждым новым достижением ты будешь всё больше верить в себя. и вскоре поймёшь, что все границы лишь в твоей голове.
⠀
🎄  ты был создан, чтобы прожить жизнь, полную любви. не смей даже думать, что ты чего-то не достоин. каждый имеет право на полноценное счастье и искреннюю любовь.
.

text: *tw* ten days after my birthday, i was sexually assaulted. since then i’ve struggled daily with anxiety, ptsd, depression- you name it. it’s been the hardest semester & the hardest three months of my life, but this tattoo is a reminder of strength. the flower- aster, is the flower of september (when i was assaulted, and also my birthday). a low and a high. serotonin, the molecule for happiness. it’s to remind me to find the joy, especially in september. here’s to hoping this brings some healing 💞 highly recommend @neckboneink for an amazing job & for making me feel so comfortable while so vulnerable!! & endlessly thankful to jade for staying by my side at svu 2 days after my assault and holding my hand when i got this tatt to commemorate it all. #metoo

text:
- what we worked on was ... data harvesting programs where we would pull data from users of apps and all of their friend networks and run that data through algorithms that could profile their personality traits and other psychological attributes, wylie told cnn’s don lemon monday evening.

wylie said the ultimate goal was to obtain information in order to exploit mental vulnerabilities that our algorithms showed that [facebook users] had.

in addition to wylie and cambridge analytica, accounts of cambridge analytica’s parent company, strategic communication laboratories, and those of a university of cambridge psychologist aleksandr kogan were also suspended.

the accounts were suspended because facebook received reports that data that had been shared with cambridge and wylie from kogan’s app may not have been completely deleted. kogan’s app was removed in 2015 and facebook said they had been previously provided certifications that the data had been deleted. - several days ago, we received reports that, contrary to the certifications we were given, not all data was deleted, facebook said friday. - we are moving aggressively to determine the accuracy of these claims. if true, this is another unacceptable violation of trust and the commitments they made. we are suspending scl/cambridge analytica, wylie and kogan from facebook, pending further information.

special counsel robert mueller asked cambridge analytica last fall to surrender emails from any of its employees who worked for the trump campaign, the wall street journal reported in december. the firm complied to the request.

diana stancy correll
washington examiner

text:
christopher wylie, who worked with a cambridge university academic to obtain the data, told the observer: “we exploited facebook to harvest millions of people’s profiles. and built models to exploit what we knew about them and target their inner demons. that was the basis the entire company was built on.” documents seen by the observer, and confirmed by a facebook statement, show that by late 2015 the company had found out that information had been harvested on an unprecedented scale. however, at the time it failed to alert users and took only limited steps to recover and secure the private information of more than 50 million individuals.

the data was collected through an app called thisisyourdigitallife, built by academic aleksandr kogan, separately from his work at cambridge university. through his company global science research (gsr), in collaboration with cambridge analytica, hundreds of thousands of users were paid to take a personality test and agreed to have their data collected for academic use.

however, the app also collected the information of the test-takers’ facebook friends, leading to the accumulation of a data pool tens of millions-strong. facebook’s “platform policy” allowed only collection of friends’ data to improve user experience in the app and barred it being sold on or used for advertising. the discovery of the unprecedented data harvesting, and the use to which it was put, raises urgent new questions about facebook’s role in targeting voters in the us presidential election. it comes only weeks after indictments of 13 russians by the special counsel robert mueller which stated they had used the platform to perpetrate “information warfare” against the us.

carole cadwalladr & emma graham-harrison
the guardian

-

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
- what we worked on was ... data harvesting programs where we would pull data from users of apps and all of their friend networks and run that data through algorithms that could profile their personality traits and other psychological attributes, wylie told cnn’s don lemon monday evening.

wylie said the ultimate goal was to obtain information in order to exploit mental vulnerabilities that our algorithms showed that [facebook users] had.

in addition to wylie and cambridge analytica, accounts of cambridge analytica’s parent company, strategic communication laboratories, and those of a university of cambridge psychologist aleksandr kogan were also suspended.

the accounts were suspended because facebook received reports that data that had been shared with cambridge and wylie from kogan’s app may not have been completely deleted. kogan’s app was removed in 2015 and facebook said they had been previously provided certifications that the data had been deleted. - several days ago, we received reports that, contrary to the certifications we were given, not all data was deleted, facebook said friday. - we are moving aggressively to determine the accuracy of these claims. if true, this is another unacceptable violation of trust and the commitments they made. we are suspending scl/cambridge analytica, wylie and kogan from facebook, pending further information.

special counsel robert mueller asked cambridge analytica last fall to surrender emails from any of its employees who worked for the trump campaign, the wall street journal reported in december. the firm complied to the request.

diana stancy correll
washington examiner

the accounts were suspended because facebook received repos that data that had been shared with cambridge and wylie from kogan’s app may not have been completely deleted. kogan’s app was removed in 2015 and facebook said they had been previously provided ceifications that the data had been deleted. - several days ago, we received repos that, contrary to the ceifications we were given, not all data was deleted, facebook said friday. - we are moving aggressively to determine the accuracy of these claims. if true, this is another unacceptable violation of trust and the commitments they made. we are suspending scl/cambridge analytica, wylie and kogan from facebook, pending fuher information.

special counsel robe mueller asked cambridge analytica last fall to surrender emails from any of its employees who worked for the trump campaign, the wall street journal repoed in december. the firm complied to the request.

diana stancy correll
washington examiner

text:
short-term memory loss is one of the many complications of ptsd (post-traumatic stress disorder.) your brains chemicals have been altered as your mind begins to unpack the trauma that has happened. 
my memory had deteriorated after i had completely cut contact. my mind began to upload a file that seems to be beyond capacity. the small files - day to day ones, tend to crash or are forgotten very quickly. 🤦🏽‍♀️ once i had made up my mind that enough was enough. i cut all contact. i didn’t say goodbye. i called out the bs and watched him scramble up excuses after excuses. i knew i was going to be the one that stopped him in his tracks.

i see a woman that is rising from the ashes. i give myself time out and patience. i absolutely love the skin i am in, the marks on my body that were left from him are now my battle wounds, each day they fade, each day i grow a little more, discover something entirely new about myself. the best part of this journey. rediscovering what i thought would never be discovered again. 💚🌿💚 .  #offmychest #hearmetoo #metoo #wecandobetter #arttherapy #creative #creativeseries #rediscoveringmyself

text:
christopher wylie, who worked with a cambridge university academic to obtain the data, told the observer: “we exploited facebook to harvest millions of people’s profiles. and built models to exploit what we knew about them and target their inner demons. that was the basis the entire company was built on.” documents seen by the observer, and confirmed by a facebook statement, show that by late 2015 the company had found out that information had been harvested on an unprecedented scale. however, at the time it failed to alert users and took only limited steps to recover and secure the private information of more than 50 million individuals.

the data was collected through an app called thisisyourdigitallife, built by academic aleksandr kogan, separately from his work at cambridge university. through his company global science research (gsr), in collaboration with cambridge analytica, hundreds of thousands of users were paid to take a personality test and agreed to have their data collected for academic use.

however, the app also collected the information of the test-takers’ facebook friends, leading to the accumulation of a data pool tens of millions-strong. facebook’s “platform policy” allowed only collection of friends’ data to improve user experience in the app and barred it being sold on or used for advertising. the discovery of the unprecedented data harvesting, and the use to which it was put, raises urgent new questions about facebook’s role in targeting voters in the us presidential election. it comes only weeks after indictments of 13 russians by the special counsel robert mueller which stated they had used the platform to perpetrate “information warfare” against the us.

carole cadwalladr & emma graham-harrison
the guardian

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text:
for many of mahachai’s migrant youth a holiday party is a rare, precious gift.

their lives are difficult, at times dangerous, and full of uncertainty. however, the joy and gratitude that emanates from their being reminds me of the true meaning of the holidays. 
thank you to my students for giving me one of the most beautiful holidays. i am so thankful for each and everyone of you. ✨💕

text:
trigger warnings: disordered eating, mental health, assualt. .
i don't own a lot of photos of myself. occasionally, my mother shares a few with me and it leaves a knot in my stomach. diet culture has sold us the lie that if we can achieve a target weight, we will be respected, successful, and happy. diet culture teaches us to conflate size with health, achievement, and well-being. .
at 23, i had reached my target bmi. at 23, i could not get out of bed in the morning without a beer. i could not get through my lunch without the fistful of cigarettes i substituted for food. i thought if i ran enough, lifted enough, fasted enough; no one would know how utterly wrecked my body and soul were from a violent sexual assualt. friends, family, therapists told me how well adjusted i was based on (my size*) my rigorous commitment to a misinterpretation of health. .
for half of my life i set a weight loss goal for myself at this time every year - and i often met those goals. i wasn't healthy. i was not happy. .
in the past 6 years, i gained weight. i also fell in love with myself for reasons that had nothing to do with my size. i had a number of achievements - i obtained my masters as a first generation student,  prioritized my mental health, redefined wellness and nutrition for myself (based on the health at every size model), and opened myself up to traveling to new countries to learn new ways of being. i set new, more challenging goals and it was every bit more fulfilling when i met them. i chose to grow. .
the reason i am sharing this is because a fat person has to deal with a constant stream of well-intentioned assholes who feel compelled to make assumptions and suggestions about your health - about your choices - and i am telling you you can resist that. you get to define health for yourself. full stop. .
and for those who judge on the basis of size - i  really hope you take this year to reflect on your own conditioning, your fear, and your own mental wellness. hate is not a good look. . 
wishing you all the very best in 2019. 
#bodypositive #bopowarriors #happynewyear #healthateverysize #newyearsameme #radicalselflove #lovebig #metoo #reflecting #healing #thriving
name: Jasmine Rucker
tweet_full:
trigger warnings: disordered eating, mental health, assualt. .
i do not own a lot of photos of myself. occasionally, my mother shares a few with me and it leaves a knot in my stomach. diet culture has sold us the lie that if we can achieve a target weight, we will be respected, successful, and happy. diet culture teaches us to conflate size with health, achievement, and well-being. .
at 23, i had reached my target bmi. at 23, i could not get out of bed in the morning without a beer. i could not get through my lunch without the fistful of cigarettes i substituted for food. i thought if i ran enough, lifted enough, fasted enough; no one would know how utterly wrecked my body and soul were from a violent sexual assualt. friends, family, therapists told me how well adjusted i was based on (my size*) my rigorous commitment to a misinterpretation of health. .
for half of my life i set a weight loss goal for myself at this time every year - and i often met those goals. i wasn't healthy. i was not happy. .
in the past 6 years, i gained weight. i also fell in love with myself for reasons that had nothing to do with my size. i had a number of achievements - i obtained my masters as a first generation student,  prioritized my mental health, redefined wellness and nutrition for myself (based on the health at every size model), and opened myself up to traveling to new countries to learn new ways of being. i set new, more challenging goals and it was every bit more fulfilling when i met them. i chose to grow. .
the reason i am sharing this is because a fat person has to deal with a constant stream of well-intentioned assholes who feel compelled to make assumptions and suggestions about your health - about your choices - and i am telling you you can resist that. you get to define health for yourself. full stop. .
and for those who judge on the basis of size - i  really hope you take this year to reflect on your own conditioning, your fear, and your own mental wellness. hate is not a good look. . 
wishing you all the very best in 2019. 
#bodypositive #bopowarriors #happynewyear #healthateverysize #newyearsameme #radicalselflove #lovebig #metoo #reflecting #healing #thriving

what an amazing year! i have been blessed to meet so many wonderful new friends and god opened the door to great opportunities to share my story, "call me master- a memoir surviving abuse". i stepped out of my comfort zone to share, educate and inspire others. to be a voice to those victims that are no longer with us. thank you for the support and love! 
if you are trapped in an abusive relationship call your lical shelter or call the police. if you know someone in an abusive relationship please don't give up on them. listen, be patient with them, and remind them they are not to blame. find resources from your local shelter or the police to help. stay safe! big hugs!

"don't get caught wanting"
so it may be true that those that won't help themselves can't be helped by you...but have you ever thought maybe they don't realize they need help! in other words a person that lives in denial is a person that's almost impossible to help.  i know this because as a victim i once lived this way. running around subconsciously crying for help but unconsciously not realizing that i needed help! my reality was so distorted & the blinders i had on was pitch black. after almost pushing everyone away i knew i needed a clearer vision & god gave me just that as i was blinded by victimization mow i see by god's healing liberty🙌 i beg you not to be caught wanting today all because you refuse to see that you are in need of help! cause when you call on god know that help is on the way 💖💖💖💖 #livelovelaugh #loveheals #loveliftedme❤🙏 #metoo #rapesurvivor #survivor #lifecoach #jesusdesirestosaveyou #jesuslovesyou #mentalhealth #helpisnotontheway #beencouraged #blacklove #blackgirlsrock #blackgirlmagic #nomore #speaklife #liftyourself #laviniasmiles #laviniaspeaks @larenztate @beyonce #faith

text:
i got my very first copy of @gtwomanmagazine today and so much excitement and gratitude is swirling around in my heart. all i can say is i am humbled by the opportunity to share my story — beauty from the ashes: my journey of transformation. my arms are wide open and my story is enormously transparent. i have swung from giddy highs to anxious lows during the process of opening up and writing more of my story for all to hear. but it’s mine. and as i say in my article, “my heart is full of joy, my life is filled with hope and my kids are thriving. i stand on my sacred ground and claim love above all else and i trust that love will be greater than any obstacle that comes my way.” thank you, my friends, for being my village, my rock to stand on, my shoulder to cry on, my feet to dance with and my sunshine on cloudy days. i have the best friends a girl could ask for and an iron clad community with hearts of gold. yes. this is my story, these are my people and this is my very best life chapter yet. #thisisme ❤️
.
www.livetrue.life
.

text:
👹⛪ happy nyeee hail satan. an excerpt from ali kellogg's article on a destruction ritual experience - "then one year, we started bringing physical objects to destroy. things that bore some kind of sentimental value we hung onto, but in reality just sat in a box in a closet somewhere and caused us negative emotions when we remembered they were there. we felt by hanging onto these objects, we were holding onto the hope of a failed relationship or the improvement of someone’s character, or a good memory we would cling to like this object was a life raft, but all it did was hurt us. we took turns smashing our objects with hammers, knives, and throwing the pieces into the fire. afterwards, i felt a sense of empowerment i had never felt before, and an epiphany. the relationship was done, but i had let it still continue to hurt me by giving power to this stupid little plastic tambourine and a box of paper. by hanging onto them, i allowed the toxicity to seep into my everyday and gave something inanimate delusional purpose.
the destruction ritual serves this very purpose — destroying objects that we have given the power to hurt us. it’s a form of self love, as you are trusting that by destroying these stupid things, you will be stronger and lighter, so to speak, after doing it. so much of our culture revolves around material possessions. our social status is assigned by what we have, our self worth is measured by what we have. we go into debt to buy cars and clothes and technology that pollutes the environment and will probably break and need to be replaced within two years anyway. in a way, you could stretch it and say the destruction ritual is your own petty way of combating the detrimental effects of capitalism."
.
.
.
.
.

text:
#actressroundtable2018 by #rajeevmasand confused me. earlier the #actorsroundtable2018 i had thoroughly enjoyed, with the soulful wisdom of #pankajtripathi tripathy, the way he wove his words, the light hearted banter and idiosyncrasies of #ranveersingh, the introspection by #vickykaushal, the passionate discourse on the craft of acting by #rajkummarrao and of course as ranveer put it, the man behind all of 2018’s #roi, #ayushmankhurrana with his usual easy going unassuming humility. they discussed on method, movies, #metoo and many more...
with the #actress i first of all found the #questions #frivolous... i don’t recall the men being asked “who was their crush”.... there wasn’t a single question on their craft... the whole panel were interrupting each other white #tabu seemingly sleepwalking...(well, we know how deftly she had pulled out a #ladymacbeth), #deepika was graceful... however two most embarrassing and disappointing part of the round table was one #ranimukherjee take on #metoo... she said in very many words, “ women should learn to avoid and also learn martial arts!!” ridiculous!! others politely tried to bring her to see the perspective, but to no avail!! the other was the question on #patriotism vs #jingoism...i totally lost what #aliabhatt wanted to say... she started with her belief in the #futulity of war to finally realising, (yes hold your breath)..”jawans at the border guarding your country” and then #anoushka  joining in to speak of her #faujidad... even questions which were meant to push the panelist towards introspecting in their process and craft turned out to be a dampner...tabu when asked in playing #simmi inn#andhadhun, a woman with no conscience, was interrupted by our #aliamiss, since she didn’t want spoilers...before she could watch the film..🙄
for me it was uncomfortable watching this... since the round table which started with the premise of celebrating #bollywood having #authorbacked roles for #women turned out to be a frivolous chat show which could have been moderated better and the questions could have been picked keeping in mind the varying range!!
